  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n- Basel Committee's recommendations in the 1990s\n- Patriot Act (2001) expanding financial monitoring\n\n3. Regulatory Enhancements\n- Increased Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Enhanced due diligence protocols\n- Stricter reporting obligations for financial institutions\n\n4. International Cooperation\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Standardized compliance frameworks\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Advanced transaction monitoring systems\n- Cybercrime prevention strategies\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency transaction tracking\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced penalties for non-compliance\n- Machine learning-based detection techniques\n\n7. Expanded Scope\n- Covering more financial instruments\n- Including non-financial businesses\n- Addressing emerging financial technologies\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, becoming more comprehensive and technologically sophisticated.",
